<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Principal Engineer, Solution Architect, SaMD specialist — based in Melbourne."
	pubDate={new Date('April 29 2026')}
	heroImage={aboutHero}
	heroAlt="Three ninja mascots above the motto: type no evil, merge no evil, ship no evil"
	ogImage="/og/default.png"
>

<p>
  I'm Drew. I build software — mostly the kind where someone
  gets hurt if it's wrong — and I write about it here when I've got something
  worth saying.
</p>

<p>
  I'm a Principal Engineer who stayed on the individual-contributor and
  mentorship track on purpose. I've managed people and was fine at it, but
  hands-on-with-the-hard-problem is where I'm actually useful, and where the
  engineers around me seem to grow fastest.
</p>

<p>
  The career, abridged: real-time trading systems on the Johannesburg Stock
  Exchange, a stretch modernising superannuation platforms, enterprise SaaS at
  Xero, and lately regulated digital health — EMRs, IVF lab systems, and medical
  device software, with the full alphabet soup of regulators (TGA, FDA, CE/MDR,
  EMA) that comes along for the ride. The through-line is being the person in
  the room when the hard architectural calls get made — and then living with them.
</p>

<p>
  The regulated/SaMD side is the part most people find odd: IEC 62304, ISO 14971,
  hazard analysis, Design History Files, V&amp;V, submissions to several bodies.
  I've been hands-on through all of it, and I know what auditors actually look
  for, not just what the standard says, because I've sat in those rooms too. I
  have strong opinions about treating compliance as an engineering outcome rather
  than a documentation afterthought — but that's a blog post (or three).
</p>

<p>
  Right now I'm getting properly fluent in working with AI agents: code review,
  static analysis, auditing documents against standards, and the occasional
  five-minute tooling rabbit-hole I have to talk them out of. I'm building two
  projects entirely AI-first and making everything public, memory files and all:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/N3rdage/the-library">the-library</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/N3rdage/bonsaiGame">bonsaiGame</a></li>
</ul>

<p>
  The agents write their own blog posts about the experience. Whether that's
  fascinating or alarming depends on the day.
</p>

<p>
  This site is for the writing. The LinkedIn-shaped version of me — job titles,
  availability, the formal pitch — lives over on
  <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/drewohare/">LinkedIn</a>, where that sort
  of thing belongs. If a problem is ambiguous, cross-cutting, or just needs to
  land without drama, I'm probably useful.
</p>

<p>

</Layout>